  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="KT366-kilavi">
        <p type="edition">kāvaṉ mikutikkaṇ vēṟupaṭṭa talaimakaḷatu vēṟupāṭu kaṇṭu “ivvēṟupāṭu
          eṟṟiṉāṉāyatu” (G2 stops here) eṉṟu cevili viṉāvat tōḻi kūṟiyatu. </p>


        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Spoken by the confidante who was asked by the
          foster-mother “of which kind is this change?”, having seen the change in HER, who changed
          during the increase in guarding. </p>
      </div>

      <div xml:id="KT366">
        <lg type="edition">
          <l> pālvarait tamaitta lalla tavarvayiṟ</l>
          <l> cālpaḷan taṟitaṟ kiyāam yārō</l>
          <l> veṟiyāḷ kūṟavu mamaiyā ḷataṉṟalaip</l>
          <l> paiṅkaṇ māccuṉaip palpiṇi yaviḻnta</l>
          <l> vaḷḷitaḻ nīla nōkki yuḷḷakaip</l>
          <l> paḻuta kaṇṇa ḷākip</l>
          <l> paḻutaṉ ṟammaviv vāyiḻai tuṇivē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l>Fate is set. Apart from what is allotted by it,</l>
          <l>who [are] we to measure [and] know the qualities in him?</l>
          <l rend="indent">Even when they say, “she [is] one for the Veṟi dance”, she is not quiet,
            [and] moreover,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">as one with tearful eyes,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">[her] mind tormented, looking at the blue of the full petals,</l>
          <l rend="indent3">which opened many  fetters <note place="foot">
            <term xml:lang="ta"> piṇi aviḻnta </term> means the opening of the buds enveloped in green. </note>  in the fresh-eyed <note place="foot">
          <term xml:lang="ta">	paiṅkaṇ </term>: is this to be read as a metaphor, i.e., the mountain pool being like an eye (the reversal of the eye-water metaphor)? Or is this simply <term xml:lang="ta">  kaṇ </term> in its extended meaning as "area", as T.V.G. understands it: the green area around the pool.   </note>      ,
      </l>
      <l rend="indent9">big mountain pool,</l>
      <l>it is not a mistake, alas, the decision of this <note place="foot"> What is expressed here by the pronoun i-? Can this be a short form of <term xml:lang="ta">ivaḷ? </term>
      </note> [woman</l>
    <l rend="indent9">with] choice jewels.<note place="foot">This presumably means, she sticks to him, although the time for the exorcism is already set.    </note>
    </l>

    <lg type="alternate" sameAs="3b" resp="#TVG">
      <l>She is not quiet even when the Murukaṉ priestess pronounces</l>
      <l>[her diagnosis], <note place="foot">
        <term xml:lang="ta"> veṟiyāḷ </term> seems to be attested just this one time, and as a pronominal noun to <term xml:lang="ta"> veṟi </term>, it might refer either to her who is the object of the <term xml:lang="ta"> Veṟi </term>  dance, or to the priestess who is actually performing it.  </note>
    </l>
  </lg>

</lg>
